Study Information
______
TITLE:
Systematizing Confidence in Open Research and Evidence (SCORE):
Direct Replication of a Research Claim from Janssen et al. (2011) in
Experimental Economics
______
AUTHORS:
Johannes Jarke-Neuert1
Cornelia E. L. Neuert2
1 Center for Earth System Research and Sustainability (CEN),
Universität Hamburg, Germany
2 Leibniz Institute for the Social Sciences in Mannheim, Germany
______
DESCRIPTION:
The present research project is one direct replication (out of three
done by three independent research teams) of a research claim from
Janssen et al. (2011) “Coordination and cooperation in asymmetric
commons dilemmas”, published in Experimental Economics, Vol.
14, pp. 547-566 (DOI 10.1007/s10683-011-9281-9). The claim
selected for replication from that paper is that in a five-player
public infrastructure investment game, tail-ender subjects will
increase investments in public infrastructure (dependent variable)
provision under the condition that they receive a fair share of the
resulting resource ﬂows from previous rounds of the game.
We independently re-implement the five-player public

infrastructure investment game from Janssen et al. (2011), in which
each player must decide 1) how much to invest in public
infrastructure (“download bandwidth”) and 2) how much to extract
from the common pool infrastructure (“how many files to
download”). The game mimics investments in an irrigation system
where the resources drawn by upstream actors limit what can be
extracted by downstream actors (“tail-enders”). See the original
study for details.
The hypothesis is that tail-ender subjects will increase investments
in public infrastructure (dependent variable) provision under the
condition that they receive a fair share of the resulting resource
ﬂows from previous rounds of the game. This is tested by
comparing the average amount of investment made by downstream
players (the “tail-ender subjects”) to upstream players using a
hierarchical linear model which
allows the authors to control for variability of individuals within an
experimental group as well as group specific error rates. The
hierarchical linear model uses investment levels in the public
infrastructure as the dependent variable, and the position of the
individual, the round number, and the relative share of tokens
(“downloaded files”) earned from resource extraction in the
previous round as independent variables. StataMP 16.1 and the
command mixed is used for the estimation procedure. The test of
the selected claim is based on an interaction effect between position
and the share of downloaded files from previous round (t - 1). A
statistically significant and positive estimate means that if
downstream participants get a higher share, they invest more in the
shared infrastructure. Janssen et al. (2011) found the interaction
effect to be statistically significant and positive for the 5-player
game with six groups (third column, table 8) - unstandardized
coefficient = 3.836, SE = .836, p < .01.
The initial target sample size is 270 observations (6 groups of 5
subjects with 9 observations each). To account for attrition and
unusable data, we collect another 45 observations (1 group of 5
subjects). If a statistically significant effect is not observed after the
first round of data collection, a second round will begin. The second
round of data collection will sample an additional 270 observations

(plus 45 safety margin) for a pooled sample of 540 observations (12
groups of 5 subjects with 9 observations each), up to 630 including
the safety margin. Power calculations were done in accordance with
the guidelines of the Social Sciences Replication Project (SSRP). The
first round of data collection achieves 90% power to detect 75% of
the original effect size. The pooled sample, if necessary, after testing
the effect on the first round of data, achieves 90% power to detect
50% of the original effect size. The power analysis rationale and R
code for this replication can be found in the power component of
the OSF project for this paper.
During the experiment, subjects are seated to computer terminals
through which they make decisions that influence their
compensation payment. In order to avoid biasing subjects for a
particular context, the experiment is presented to the participants
not as an common-pool resource experiment but, rather, as a game
of downloading digital files where subject A has priority access to
the available bandwidth (the common-pool resource) over subject
B. The experiment utilizes a dashboard to allow subjects to make
decisions and display information about the experiment. In each
round, before “downloading” can begin, subjects decide about how
many tokens to invest in creating bandwidth. Subjects are informed
about how much each of the subjects invested, and how much
bandwidth was created based on their total investment. Next, there
is a period of 100 seconds during which subjects can “download
files”. Using the dashboard, subjects click on images of files to start
downloading and they see an animation of the downloading
process. They are shown how much bandwidth is available for each
subject and how much time is left in the downloading period. The
real time interaction is purposely chosen to include the need for
coordination to solve the asymmetry problem. The monetary
returns depend on the production function as a function of the
number of files downloaded. When only a few files are downloaded
no tokens are earned. This resembles the case in which a limited
amount of water is received by a farmer which is insufficient to
grow a crop. When the number of files
downloaded increases, the number of tokens earned increases
sharply. This reflects the fact that enough water has been collected
to grow crops. If more than 7 files are downloaded, the extra

reward is marginal. This reflects the fact that beyond a certain
amount of water there is saturation for the crop growth. Thus, if ten
files are downloaded, 20 tokens are earned. The total earnings of a
player are the number of tokens not invested in the common
resource plus the number of tokens earned by downloading files.
Before the subjects can start the experiment, they must go through a
number of
instructions which are followed by a quiz. They can only start when
all quiz questions
are answered correctly. The experiment starts with two practice
rounds that do
not count toward player earnings followed by ten rounds which are
played for monetary returns. Before each round, the players can
exchange text messages among those
within the same group for 60 seconds.
After finishing the experiment, subjects are paid and released. The
interactions are “double-blind” anonymous, no personal identities
are revealed to the participants nor the experimenters.
HYPOTHESIS:
In a five-player public infrastructure investment game, tail-ender
subjects will increase investments in public infrastructure
(dependent variable) provision under the condition that they
receive a fair share of the resulting resource ﬂows from previous
rounds of the game. (For the testable null hypothesis see section
“study design”)
Design Plan
______
STUDY TYPE:

Observational Study - Data is collected from study subjects that are
not randomly assigned to a treatment.
______
BLINDING:
Subjects will not know the treatment group to which they have
been assigned. Personnel who interact directly with the study
subjects will not be aware of the assigned treatments. (Commonly
known as “double blind”). There is no additional blinding in this
study.
______
STUDY DESIGN:
We independently re-implement the five-player public
infrastructure investment game from Janssen et al. (2011), in which
each player must decide 1) how much to invest in public
infrastructure (“download bandwidth”) and 2) how much to extract
from the common pool infrastructure (“how many files to
download”). The game mimics
investments in an irrigation system where the resources drawn by
upstream actors limit what can be extracted by downstream actors
(“tail-enders”). See the original study for details.
The hypothesis is that tail-ender subjects will increase investments
in public infra-structure (dependent variable) provision under the
condition that they receive a fair share of the resulting resource
ﬂows from previous rounds of the game. This is tested by
comparing the average amount of investment made by downstream
players (the “tail-ender subjects”) to upstream players using a
hierarchical linear model which allows the authors to control for
variability of individuals within an experimental group as well as
group specific error rates. The hierarchical linear model uses
investment levels in the public infrastructure as the dependent
variable, and the position of the individual, the round number, and
the relative share of tokens (“downloaded files”) earned from

resource extraction in the previous round as independent variables.
StataMP 16.1 and the command mixed is used for the estimation
procedure. The test of the selected claim is based on an interaction
effect between Position and the share of downloaded files from
previous round (t -1). A statistically significant and positive
estimate means that if downstream participants get higher share,
they invest more in the shared infrastructure. Janssen et al. (2011)
found the interaction effect to be statistically significant and
positive for the 5-player game with six groups (third column, table
8) - unstandardized coefficient = 3.836, SE = .836, p < .01. Our
Null hypothesis for the replication attempt is, as it was in the
original study, that the coefficient is zero. The measure of
replication success is whether our study also rejects the null while
assuming 75% of the effect size that was originally observed for the
purposes of calculating the required sample size.
