Analysis Plan
______
STATISTICAL MODELS:
The hypothesis is that tail-ender subjects will increase investments

in public infrastructure (dependent variable) provision under the
condition that they receive a fair share of the resulting resource
ﬂows from previous rounds of the game. This is tested by
comparing the average amount of investment made by downstream
players (the “tail-ender subjects”) to upstream players using a
hierarchical linear model which allows the authors to control for
variability of individuals within an experimental group as well as
group specific error rates. Specifically, the model is an instance of a
linear mixed model, which is a generalization of linear regression
allowing for the inclusion of random effects other than those
associated with the overall error term. In matrix notation,
y=Xϕ+Zρ+ϵ
where y is a n×1 vector of outcomes, X is a n×p covariate matrix
for the fixed effects ϕ, and Z is a n×q covariate matrix for the
random effects ρ. The n×1 vector of errors is assumed to be
multivariate normal with mean zero and variance matrix σϵ2R. The
fixed portion Xϕ is analogous to the linear predictor from a
standard OLS regression with ϕ being the regression coefficients to
be estimated. For the random portion Zρ+ϵ it is assumed that ρ has
variance-covariance matrix G and that ρ is orthogonal to ϵ. The
random effects ρ are not directly estimated (although they may be
predicted), but instead are characterized by the elements of G,
known as variance components, that are estimated along with the
overall residual variance σϵ2 and the residual-variance parameters
that are contained within R. The general forms of the design
matrices X and Z allow estimation for a broad class of linear
models, inter alia multilevel mixed-effects designs (also called
hierarchical designs because the grouping structure of the data may
consist of multiple levels of nested groups) that is used in Janssen et
al. (2011) and in our replication study. The StataMP 16.1 command
(that we use) is
mixed,which replaces xtmixed used in older Stata versions
including the one used by Janssen et al. (2011).
Specifically, we fit a multilevel model that uses investment levels in
the public infrastructure (nvst) as the dependent variable, and the
position of the individual (pstn), the round number (rnd), and the
relative share of tokens (“downloaded files”) earned from resource

extraction in the previous round (shr) as independent variables,
running the code
generate pstnshr = pstn * shr
mixed nvst pstn shr pstnshr rnd || ndvl: || grp:
The model is fitted by maximum likelihood regression.
Mathematically, the model organizes the n observations as a series
of M clusters
yj=Xjϕ+Zjρj+ϵj
for j=1,...,M, with cluster j consisting of nj observations.The
outcome yj comprises the rows of y corresponding with the jth
cluster, with Xj and ϵj defined analogously. The random effects
ρjcan now be thought of as M realizations of a q×1 vector that is
normally distributed with mean zero and q×q variance matrix. The
matrix Zj is the nj×q design matrix for the jth cluster random
effects. Because individuals are nested within groups, the model is a
three-level mixed-effects model with random intercepts at both the
individual and group levels. Formally,
yjk=Xjkϕ+Zjk3rdρk3rd+Zjk2ndρjk2nd+ϵkj
for i=1,...,njk first-level observations nested within j=1,...,Mk
second-level (individual) clusters, which are nested in k=1,...,M
third-level (group) clusters.
The test of the selected claim is based on an interaction effect
between position and the share of downloaded files from previous
round (pstnshr). A statistically significant and positive estimate
means that if downstream participants get higher share, they invest
more in the shared infrastructure. Since pstn is actually a factor
variable, we also report the results of
mixed nvst b(1).pstn##c.shr rnd || ndvl: || grp:
______

TRANSFORMATIONS:
Not applicable.
______
INFERENCE CRITERIA:
Criteria for a successful replication attempt for the SCORE project is
a statistically significant effect (alpha = .05, two tailed) in the
same pattern as the original study. Janssen et al. (2011) found the
focal interaction effect (see section “study design” and “statistical
models”) to be statistically significant and positive for the 5-player
game with six groups, with an unstandardized coefficient = 3.836,
SE = .836, p < .01. Hence, for
this replication attempt, the SCORE criteria are met if we can reject
the Null that the coefficient of pstnshr is equal to zero at p < .05,
and the coefficient is positive.
______
DATA EXCLUSIONS:
In the unlikely event of missings in any of the variables, the whole
group will be excluded from the analysis. If there is suspicious data,
the estimates of a regression without that data are reported in
addition to the estimates based on the full dataset, and the
robustness of the focal coefficient is evaluated.
______
MISSING DATA:
The only possible sources of missing data are (i) a participant
leaving the study and (ii) technical data recording errors. Both are
very rare at the WiSo Laboratories. However, if either case happens,
the data of the whole group to which the respective subjects was

assigned must be excluded from the analysis.
______
EXPLORATORY ANALYSIS:
Not applicable.
______
Other
______
DEVIATIONS AND OTHER INFORMATION:
Our replication study will copy the original study as close as
possible; we do not plan any deviation. In case deviations become
necessary during the implementation process, we will keep them as
small as possible.
